para.para.body:
Correct! - To see why a shear map 
                     S\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[2]
                   is, in general, not distance preserving, consider the vector 
                     \Vect{n}
                   with respect to which we are shearing (in the picture above, this is 
                     \StdBss{2}
                  ). It has length 
                     1
                  , and gets transformed into the vector 
                     \Vect{n}+\Vect{s}
                  , where 
                     \Vect{s}
                   is the shear vector. So, unless 
                     \Vect{s}=\Vect{0}
                  , the shear transformation increases the length of some vectors. Therefore it is not distance preserving.

Correct! – A projection can reduce certain distances. For example: in the picture above, consider the vector 
                     \Vect{c}
                  . Its length is positive. But it projects to the zero vector. Therefore the projection does not preserve all distances.
